<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-048-097 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 320 737</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Sources  Oct 1991 v2 n10 p77(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Help for DOS 5.0. (Flambeaux Software Inc.'s DOS Help 5.0 userhelp program) (Forum)(Brief Article) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brenesal, Barry.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Flambeaux Software Inc. (Product introduction).andO;Product:   DOS Help! 5.0 (Educational software) (Product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionEducational SoftwareOn-Line Help Files.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Whether you like DOS or not, chances are you don't like DOS manuals.andP;  They'vegarnered a reputation for inadequate information and presentation.andO;Fortunately, you can rely on Flambeaux Software's (Glendale, CA,800-833-7355, 818-500-0044) DOS Help series of hypertext programs.andP;  And nowthat DOS 5.0 is out, so too is Flambeaux's DOS Help 5.0 release ($49.95direct from Flabeaux).andP;  It adds new options to an already fast, thorough, andreliable product.andM;A strength of the previous DOS Help versions is a wide variety of indexingsolutions to simplify and speed user access to the program.andM;DOS Help 3.0, for instance, offers users a glossary, subject index, beginnercommand set, DOS command groups (like keyboard, disk, and file), analphabetized command catalog, grouping by function (such as disk commands andDOS utilities), and nearly 90 command-related chapters.andM;DOS Help 5.0 expands upon this with nearly 220 subjects in a general indexand an extensive chapter that outlines every DOS change since version 1.0.andO;Each discussed command is hypertext-active, letting you jump to a relevantarea for more details.andM;DOS Help 5.0 also provides 16 chapters gathered under a new category, systemoptimization.andP;  These tutorials provide accurate, hands-on information aboutfine-tuning DOS 5.0 for your particular system.andM;You'll find discussions of DOS in high memory, HIMEM.SYS, and optimizing diskinterleave, to name just a few.andP;  Facts are augmented wherever pertinent withsuggestions and hints appropriate to each microprocessor.andM;As with previous releases of the DOS Help series, DOS Help 5.0 loads from thecommand line or in TSR mode, consuming approximately 59K of RAM.andP;  The newversion also includes a switch that loads it into high memory as a TSR on386-based computers, without any reduction in conventional memory.andO;</TEXT></DOC>